<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<jmeterTestPlan version="1.2" properties="5.0" jmeter="5.6.3">
<hashTree>
<TestPlan guiclass="TestPlanGui" testclass="TestPlan" testname="BWT Money Time" enabled="true">
  <stringProp name="TestPlan.comments">BWT MONEY-TIME LOAD TEST  (40 singers sign up at once + 60 audience polling = 100 concurrent)

BEFORE RUNNING, configure a throwaway event from OUTSIDE (browser admin / People's-Choice admin):
  - Constance PASSCODE        = dev
  - Constance EVENT_SKU       = LOADTEST   (any non-empty value; required to open the app)
  - Constance FREEBIE_TICKET  = 123456     (must match the hardcoded order-id below)
  - Enable feature flag CAN_SIGNUP
These match the hardcoded defaults in this plan, so you can just hit Run with no -J flags.
Override any of them with -Jpasscode= -Jfreebie= etc. if you change the event.

RUN (headless, with HTML dashboard + pass/fail):
  jmeter -n -t money-time.jmx -Jrun_id=$(date +%s) -l result.jtl -e -o report
  python3 verdict.py result.jtl        # PASS/FAIL vs SLA

FLOW per singer: login (clustered via ramp) -&gt; warm up polling on /home (-Jwarmup loops) -&gt;
  open /add_song -&gt; RENDEZVOUS (all 40 wait) -&gt; POST /add_song_request with a short name typed
  fast ('ready set go') -&gt; then edit to the real name (manage_songs/get_current_songs/update_song).
Audience just log in and poll. Trivia: /get_active_question is always polled; /get_selected_answer
only fires during an ACTIVE trivia round (404s otherwise) so it is a separate scenario, not money-time.
LYRICS/EXA: the edit renames to a real song from songs.csv (distinct per singer), which re-fires the
get_lyrics celery task -&gt; exa.ai really searches. So ~40 real lyric fetches per run (uses Exa quota).
Keep songs.csv next to the jmx (scp it to bwt-stress too); override path with -Jsongs_csv=.

KNOBS: -Jsingers=40 -Jaudience=60 -Jduration=300 -Jramp=1 -Jwarmup=8 -Jsla=2000 -Jpoll_interval=1000
       -Jhost=broadwaywithatwist.xyz -Jrun_id=&lt;unique each run, avoids 'already logged in'&gt;
Run the laptop only as a small functional check (e.g. -Jsingers=5 -Jaudience=5 -Jduration=30);
do the real 100-user tier benchmark from the bwt-stress EC2 box (in-region). Reset the DB when done.</stringProp>
  <boolProp name="TestPlan.functional_mode">false</boolProp>
  <boolProp name="TestPlan.tearDown_on_shutdown">true</boolProp>
  <boolProp name="TestPlan.serialize_threadgroups">false</boolProp>
  <elementProp name="TestPlan.user_defined_variables" elementType="Arguments" guiclass="ArgumentsPanel" testclass="Arguments" testname="User Defined Variables" enabled="true">
    <collectionProp name="Arguments.arguments"/>
  </elementProp>
  <stringProp name="TestPlan.user_define_classpath"></stringProp>
</TestPlan>
<hashTree>
<Arguments guiclass="ArgumentsPanel" testclass="Arguments" testname="Config" enabled="true"><collectionProp name="Arguments.arguments"><elementProp name="HOST" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">HOST</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(host,broadwaywithatwist.xyz)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="PROTOCOL" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">PROTOCOL</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(protocol,https)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="PORT" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">PORT</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(port,443)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="PASSCODE" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">PASSCODE</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(passcode,dev)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="FREEBIE" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">FREEBIE</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(freebie,123456)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="DURATION" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">DURATION</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(duration,300)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="WARMUP_LOOPS" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">WARMUP_LOOPS</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(warmup,8)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="POLL_INTERVAL" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">POLL_INTERVAL</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(poll_interval,1000)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="SLA_MS" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">SLA_MS</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(sla,2000)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="RUN_ID" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">RUN_ID</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(run_id,run${__time(YMDHMS)})}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp><elementProp name="SONGS_CSV" elementType="Argument">
  <stringProp name="Argument.name">SONGS_CSV</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.value">${__P(songs_csv,songs.csv)}</stringProp>
  <stringProp name="Argument.metadata">=</stringProp>
</elementProp></collectionProp></Arguments>
